ters covering the important developments in housing policy that have taken place since the publication of the second edition in 1995. Spanning more than eighty years, from the Great Depression to the first two years of the Obama administration, the book argues that while our nation's policy makers have learned a great deal about how to create and implement successful housing programs, the United States, as a country, has yet to summon the political will to address the urgent housing needs of its many citizens who are unable to afford decent housing on their own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aHousing -- United States -- History. 0aHousing policy -- United States -- History. 0aHousing policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aHousingzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aHistory : Social and Cultural History. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aPublic Policy : Housing. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 4aPublic Policy : Urban and Regional Planning. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781438441689?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438441689423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438441689/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles